Consider a chemist who is studying the rate of a particular chemical reaction. This reaction can be modeled by a system of differential equations, where $x(t)$ and $y(t)$ represent the concentrations of two chemicals involved in the reaction at time $t$. The system of differential equations is given by:

\begin{align*}
\frac{dx(t)}{dt} &= -2x(t) + y(t)\\
\frac{dy(t)}{dt} &= x(t) - 3y(t)
\end{align*}

Given that the initial conditions are $x(0) = 1$ and $y(0) = 2$, find the explicit form of $x(t)$ and $y(t)$.
